nodes.title: Recolor
widgets_values:
The ReVision section does NOT take into account the positive prompt defined in the prompt section, but it considers the negative prompt.

Also, ReVision images are not further passed to the Refiner or the FaceDetailer, for now.

If you enable the ReVision switch in the Master Switch node, it makes sense to disable all other switches.


To change the importance of each source image, change the corresponding weight.

The "Efficient Loader" node is preferred to the standard "Load Checkpoint" node because it can interact with the "XY Plot" node.

There is no real need to connect positive and negative prompts to the "Efficient Loader" node other than to make the "XY Plot" work.

nodes.title: Start Here
widgets_values:
AP Workflow v3.1 includes the following functions:


*SDXL Base+Refiner
All images are generated using both the SDXL Base model and the Refiner model, each automatically configured to perform a certain amount of diffusion steps according to the "Step Ratio" formula defined in the dedicated widget.

Notice: You must set the Step Ratio Switch to 2.


*Fine-tuned SDXL (or just the SDXL Base)
All images are generated just with the SDXL Base model or a fine-tuned SDXL model that requires no Refiner.

You MUST set the Step Ration Switch to 1.


*XY Plot
The XY Plot function will generate images with the SDXL Base+Refiner models, or the fine-tuned SDXL model, according to your configuration. To activate it, follow the instructions in the dedicated section of the green area.

Notice that the XY Plot function can work in conjunction with ControlNet, the Detailer, and the Upscalers.


*ControlNet XL
You can also condition your images with the ControlNet preprocessors, including the new OpenPose preprocessor compatible with SDXL. Activate each one (currently five are configured) with its dedicated switch in the purple section of the workflow.

Notice that the ControlNet conditioning can work in conjunction with the XY Plot function, the Refiner, the Detailer, and the Upscalers.


*ReVision
An alternative to the SDXL Base+Refiner models, or the fine-tuned SDXL model.

Notice that the ReVision model does NOT take into account the positive prompt defined in the prompt builder section, but it considers the negative prompt.

Also, notice that ReVision can work in conjunction with the Detailer and the Upscalers.

If you enable the ReVision engine, it makes sense to disable the SDXL Base+Refiner switch and the Fine-Tuned SDXL switch.


*Detailer
The Detailer will identify small and large faces, generating higher resolution for both, according to two distinct configurations.

Notice that the Detailer can be used with or without the Upscalers.


*Upscalers
There are two Upscalers in sequence. You can use only the 1st or both the 1st and the 2nd, by enabling them in the Master Switch. Once you do it, any image generated by the SDXL Base+Refiner models, the fine-tuned SDXL model, or the ReVision model will be upscaled.

Notice that the Upscalers will also upscale images that are processed by the Detailer, if the latter is enabled.

*Prompt Builder
You can use a (very simple) prompt builder to quickly switch between your three most used types and styles of image for the positive prompt, and your three most used prompts for negative prompts. Or you can just have the old-fashioned single prompt box.

nodes.title: Prompt Guidance
widgets_values:
From the documentation (https://github.com/comfyanonymous/ComfyUI):

You can use () to change the emphasis of a word or phrase like: (good code:1.2) or (bad code:0.8). The default emphasis for () is 1.1. To use () characters in your actual prompt escape them like \( or \).

You can use {day|night}, for wildcard/dynamic prompts. With this syntax "{wild|card|test}" will be randomly replaced by either "wild", "card" or "test" by the frontend every time you queue the prompt. To use {} characters in your actual prompt escape them like: \{ or \}.

Dynamic prompts also support C-style comments, like // comment or /* comment */.

To use a textual inversion concepts/embeddings in a text prompt put them in the models/embeddings directory and use them in the CLIPTextEncode node like this (you can omit the .pt extension):

embedding:embedding_filename.pt
